From: NextOS Elite Edition
Subject: [PATCH] Glitch64: bump fragment precision lowp -> mediump (Mali-450)

Mali-450 (Utgard) lowp precision is 8-bit (-2..2 range). N64 combiners
accumulate texture colors and modulators across multiple cycles —
lowp truncation causes color quantization that shows as black or banded
areas, especially in dark scenes / shadows / transparency.

mediump (16-bit, -2^14..2^14) is the minimum safe precision for combiner
math. Mali-450 implements mediump as fp16, GPU-native — same speed as lowp
on modern Mali drivers.

Reference: https://developer.arm.com/documentation/100614/0314/
"Avoid lowp precision in fragment shaders — it provides only 9-bit
precision, which is not enough for many modern visual effects."

--- a/src/Glitch64/OGLEScombiner.cpp
+++ b/src/Glitch64/OGLEScombiner.cpp
@@ -148,7 +148,7 @@ SHADER_VARYING
 
 static const char* fragment_shader_header =
 SHADER_HEADER
-"precision lowp float;             \n"
+"precision mediump float;          \n"
 "uniform sampler2D texture0;       \n"
 "uniform sampler2D texture1;       \n"
 "uniform sampler2D ditherTex;      \n"
